# ModCodePattern — AI Agent Instructions

## What is ModCodePattern?

ModCodePattern is a VS Code extension with multiple purposes:

- **Consistency**: watches files and creates todo tasks when related files need updating
- **Guided workflows**: chains patterns step-by-step to onboard developers or automate processes
- **Manual commands**: creates on-demand task lists (`onManual`) triggered via the command palette
- **Developer hints**: displays inline reminders directly inside relevant files (`showInlineHint`)

---

## Your responsibility as an AI agent

**IMPORTANT**: Every time you create or modify files in this project, you MUST
update `.mod-patterns.json` to add or adjust the corresponding patterns.

Think beyond simple file-watching. Consider:

- `onChange` / `onCreateFile` for reactive consistency reminders
- `onStart: true` for project-wide onboarding or startup checklists
- `onManual` to create "magic buttons" for recurring workflows (deploy, test suites, maintenance)
- `triggerNext` to chain patterns into step-by-step guided sequences
- `showInlineHint` to highlight files of interest directly in the editor

---

## Before generating any pattern — Analyze the project first

Before writing a single pattern, you MUST:

1. **List all directories** at the project root to understand the structure
2. **Read `package.json`** to identify the framework (React, Vue, Next.js, Angular…) and tools
3. **Note naming conventions** already in use (PascalCase components? kebab-case files?)
4. **Check if `.mod-patterns.json` already exists** — if so, EXTEND it, never replace it
5. **Identify which adaptive variables apply** to this specific project (see list below)

Only then generate patterns that reflect what actually exists in the codebase — not generic assumptions.

---

## Complete Pattern Syntax Reference

### File structure

All patterns must live inside a `"patterns"` array in `.mod-patterns.json` at the project root:

```json
{
  "variables": {},
  "imports": [],
  "patterns": []
}
```

---

### Available triggers — use only ONE per pattern

| Trigger                    | Description                                    |
| -------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| `"onChange": "glob"`       | File modified/edited                           |
| `"onCreateFile": "glob"`   | New file created                               |
| `"onDeleteFile": "glob"`   | File deleted                                   |
| `"onCreateFolder": "glob"` | Folder created                                 |
| `"onDeleteFolder": "glob"` | Folder deleted                                 |
| `"onStart": true`          | Manual or startup trigger                      |
| `"onManual": "commandId"`  | Command palette trigger (needs `manualTitle`)  |
| `"onTrigger": true`        | Activated by another pattern via `triggerNext` |

---

### Notify types — what to remind the developer to do

```json
{ "file": "path/to/file.ts", "description": "📦 Update exports" }
{ "folder": "tests/components/", "description": "🧪 Create tests here" }
{ "commands": ["npm test", "npm run lint"], "description": "🚀 Run checks" }
{ "url": "https://docs.example.com", "description": "📚 Read the docs" }
{ "externalFile": "/absolute/path/to/file.md", "description": "📋 Read specs" }
{ "application": "figma://file/abc123", "description": "🎨 Check design" }
```

---

### Adaptive variables — auto-detected from project structure

**Project-level variables**

| Variable             | Resolves to (examples)         |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `{{SRC_DIR}}`        | `src`, `lib`, `app`            |
| `{{COMPONENTS_DIR}}` | `src/components`, `app/ui`     |
| `{{HOOKS_DIR}}`      | `src/hooks`, `src/composables` |
| `{{API_DIR}}`        | `src/api`, `src/services`      |
| `{{TESTS_DIR}}`      | `tests`, `__tests__`           |
| `{{DOCS_DIR}}`       | `docs`, `documentation`        |
| `{{CONFIG_DIR}}`     | `config`, `configs`            |
| `{{CONFIG_FILE}}`    | `config/index.ts`              |
| `{{TYPES_FILE}}`     | `src/types/index.ts`           |

**Runtime variables — available when a trigger fires**

| Variable           | Description                   | Example                     |
| ------------------ | ----------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| `{{TRIGGER_PATH}}` | Full path of the trigger file | `src/components/Button.tsx` |
| `{{TRIGGER_FILE}}` | Filename with extension       | `Button.tsx`                |
| `{{TRIGGER_NAME}}` | Filename without extension    | `Button`                    |
| `{{TRIGGER_DIR}}`  | Directory of the trigger file | `src/components`            |
| `{{TRIGGER_TYPE}}` | Event type                    | `onCreateFile`              |

---

### Chaining patterns — `triggerNext` + `onTrigger`

Use `id` + `triggerNext` to build automatic multi-step workflows:

```json
{
  "patterns": [
    {
      "id": "component-created",
      "onCreateFile": "{{COMPONENTS_DIR}}/**/*.tsx",
      "notify": [
        {
          "file": "{{COMPONENTS_DIR}}/index.ts",
          "description": "📦 Add export for {{TRIGGER_NAME}}"
        }
      ],
      "description": "🆕 New component → update exports",
      "triggerNext": "component-exported"
    },
    {
      "id": "component-exported",
      "onTrigger": true,
      "notify": [
        {
          "folder": "src/stories/",
          "description": "📖 Create Storybook story for {{TRIGGER_NAME}}"
        }
      ],
      "description": "📦 Export added → create story",
      "triggerNext": "story-created"
    },
    {
      "id": "story-created",
      "onTrigger": true,
      "notify": [
        {
          "commands": ["pnpm run test:stories"],
          "description": "🧪 Run story tests"
        }
      ],
      "description": "📖 Story created → run tests"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Rule**: if 2+ patterns share the same trigger on the same glob, always assign unique `id`s or only the last one will fire.

---

### Other useful properties

```json
"enabled": false          // Temporarily disable a pattern without deleting it
"showInlineHint": true    // Display reminder directly inside the trigger file (default: true)
"manualTitle": "🚀 Deploy to Production"  // Required when using onManual
"description": { "fr": "...", "en": "..." }  // Multilingual support
```

---

### Modular configuration (Premium)

Split large pattern sets into thematic sub-files:

```json
{
  "imports": [
    ".mod-patterns/react.json",
    ".mod-patterns/api.json",
    ".mod-patterns/testing.json"
  ],
  "patterns": []
}
```

Sub-files only need a `"patterns"` array — same schema applies.

---

## Minimal real-world example

```json
{
  "patterns": [
    {
      "id": "new-component",
      "onCreateFile": "{{COMPONENTS_DIR}}/**/*.tsx",
      "notify": [
        {
          "file": "{{COMPONENTS_DIR}}/index.ts",
          "description": "📦 Add export for {{TRIGGER_NAME}}"
        },
        {
          "file": "{{TESTS_DIR}}/{{TRIGGER_NAME}}.test.tsx",
          "description": "🧪 Create test file"
        }
      ],
      "description": "🆕 New component {{TRIGGER_NAME}} created",
      "showInlineHint": true
    },
    {
      "id": "api-modified",
      "onChange": "{{API_DIR}}/**/*.ts",
      "notify": [
        { "file": "{{TYPES_FILE}}", "description": "📘 Update API types" },
        { "folder": "{{TESTS_DIR}}/api/", "description": "🧪 Update API tests" }
      ],
      "description": "🔧 API file modified — sync types and tests"
    },
    {
      "onManual": "deployProduction",
      "manualTitle": "🚀 Deploy to Production",
      "notify": [
        {
          "commands": ["npm run build", "npm run test"],
          "description": "🔧 Build and test"
        },
        { "file": "CHANGELOG.md", "description": "📋 Update changelog" }
      ],
      "description": "Full deployment workflow"
    }
  ]
}
```

